Rules and replacement logic
- Replace integers divisible by 3 with the token fizz.
- Replace integers divisible by 5 with the token buzz.
- Replace integers divisible by both 3 and 5 (i.e., divisible by 15) with the token fizzbuzz.
- Counting is sequential starting from any integer (commonly 1). Each number is evaluated for divisibility and replaced accordingly.
- When multiple divisibility rules apply, the combined rule (both 3 and 5) supersedes the single rules.

Variants and edge rules
- Additional divisibility rules may be added (e.g., 7) with the same behaviour: divisibility triggers substitution.
- A digit-containing rule variant: if a number contains a digit (e.g., contains '5'), treat it as matching the corresponding divisibility rule (e.g., 52 triggers the rule for 5).
- Different output tokens may be used; implementations must ensure rule precedence is defined (e.g., digit-containing rule vs divisibility).

Implementation notes for programs
- Minimal algorithm: loop i from start to end; for each i compute (i % 3 === 0), (i % 5 === 0); select output: fizzbuzz if both true, fizz if only 3, buzz if only 5, else numeric string of i.
- For performance on large ranges, avoid repeated string concatenation per number; use buffered output append and write in chunks.
- Deterministic ordering: evaluate combined rule first (i % 15 === 0) or evaluate components and combine.

SUPPLEMENTARY DETAILS
- Typical range: 1..N where N is caller-specified. Many interview tasks use N = 100.
- Output format: newline-separated tokens or array of strings for programmatic consumption.
- Internationalisation: tokens are language strings; implementations can parameterize tokens (e.g., {div3:'fizz',div5:'buzz'}).

REFERENCE DETAILS
- No external APIs required. Primitive operations used: integer modulo operator %, equality checks, loop constructs (for/while), conditional branching (if/else), array push/append and join, or stream write.
- Example evaluation ordering: if (i % 15 === 0) output fizzbuzz; else if (i % 3 === 0) output fizz; else if (i % 5 === 0) output buzz; else output i.toString().
- Language-agnostic pattern: compute booleans d3 = (i % 3 == 0), d5 = (i % 5 == 0); output depends on (d3, d5) tuple.

